The verdict: ARKit is the foundation. FLAME is optional internal plumbing.
ARKit's 52 blendshapes is the de facto cross-platform production standard
Despite the name, ARKit blendshapes are not "Apple-only" — they have become the lingua franca of real-time face animation across the industry:

Unreal Engine MetaHuman — ARKit 52 is the primary input interface (Live Link Face streaming). Internally MetaHuman uses ~130 proprietary curves for quality, but the external API is ARKit.
Unity — official ARKit Face Tracking package
VRM (the VTuber avatar format) — ARKit blendshapes as the expression standard
VRChat, VSeeFace, VMagicMirror — all ARKit
Ready Player Me — ARKit morphtargets natively
MediaPipe — Google deliberately adopted Apple's 52 named blendshapes as output. MediaPipe Face Landmarker outputs ARKit blendshape scores by name. Supporting MediaPipe = supporting ARKit automatically.
NVIDIA Audio2Face — generates the ARKit 52 core set plus extensions
Not supporting ARKit is not a technical problem — it's a market isolation problem. You'd be incompatible with MetaHuman, VRM, VRChat, all VR platforms, and every face tracking app built in the last four years.

FLAME's actual status in production: absent until 2023, and still absent
Critical finding: FLAME was non-commercial research-only until the CC-BY-4.0 license in 2023. No production pipeline was built on it because it was legally unusable. Even post-licensing, zero major engines, VR platforms, or commercial avatar tools have adopted it. It's a research standard with a beautiful parametric structure that the industry never built tooling around.

What FLAME is good for:

3D reconstruction from photos (DECA, EMOCA, SMIRK) — extracting face parameters from images
Generation (RigFace, Arc2Face expression adapter) — conditioning diffusion models
Research reproducibility — it's citable, well-understood, and everyone in research uses it
What FLAME is NOT good for:

Real-time tracking (100–500ms per frame vs 1ms for ARKit)
Direct engine integration (no Unreal/Unity FLAME node exists)
Live VTuber workflows (VTube Studio/VSeeFace have no FLAME path)
FLAME is not architecturally load-bearing for generation
This is the key finding from the second research thread. You can skip FLAME for generation:

LivePortrait (production, 12.8ms on RTX 4090) skips FLAME entirely — uses implicit keypoints directly
Arc2Face's blendshape variant doesn't render FLAME mesh — just takes coefficient vectors as cross-attention input. Those vectors could theoretically be ARKit 52-d instead of FLAME 100-d
3D Gaussian Blendshapes (SIGGRAPH 2024) is self-contained — learns its own blendshape representation from video
Meta's Codec Avatars use Gaussians + FACS-based blendshapes, not FLAME
FLAME appears everywhere in research because: it's citable, it was available before CC-BY-4.0 (for research), it has clean disentanglement (shape/expression/pose PCA spaces are orthogonal), and it was the only game in town for 3D face reconstruction. Not because generation quality depends on FLAME's specific formulation.

The one untested gap: ARKit blendshapes → diffusion generation has no published paper. Arc2Face conditions on FLAME's 100-component expression PCA; training a variant that takes ARKit 52-d vectors directly hasn't been published. This is a gap, not an impossibility — the vectors are just control inputs.

The right architecture

INPUT (capture)          INTERNAL                    OUTPUT
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
ARKit (iPhone 60fps)  ─┐
MediaPipe (webcam)    ─┼─→  ARKit 52-d blendshapes  ─→  real-time
iFacialMocap          ─┘         (the API boundary)       renderer

                              ↕ ~1ms solve (optional)

                         FLAME coefficients           ─→  generation
                         (internal use for             (Arc2Face/
                          RigFace/Arc2Face)             RigFace)
                              ↕
                         ARKit 52-d blendshapes       ─→  export to
                         (output for engine            MetaHuman,
                          compatibility)               VRM, VRChat
ARKit is both input and output. FLAME is an optional internal representation for the generation step if you want the disentanglement properties. The ARKit↔FLAME bridge is a least-squares solve, ~1ms, already has a Python library, and is not a fundamental problem.

The bridge question answered directly
How critical is having FLAME in the pipeline?

For animation of a pre-built avatar: not critical at all. ARKit blendshapes drive everything that matters directly.

For generation (creating a new face from a description or embedding): currently necessary if you want to use the best available models (Arc2Face, RigFace). But it's an implementation detail, not an API requirement. The user never needs to see FLAME.

For product compatibility: actively harmful if exposed externally. No production tool speaks FLAME. Expose ARKit; use FLAME internally if needed.

The bridge you actually want to build is not FLAME↔ARKit (that's a known solved 1ms operation). The bridge worth building is:

ARKit input → your avatar system (so any iPhone/MediaPipe user can drive it)
Your avatar → ARKit blendshape output (so the avatar works in MetaHuman, VRM, VRChat)
That's the integration that makes you compatible with the entire production ecosystem.

Bottom line per standard
Use as external API	Use internally	Build on top of
ARKit 52	Yes — it's the industry API	Fine	Yes — this is your foundation
MediaPipe	Yes, outputs ARKit format anyway	Fine	Use as a capture input layer
FLAME	No — nobody speaks it	Yes, for generation quality	No — no production ecosystem
FACS	No — theory not implementation	Useful for thinking	No
